How the pom.xml Knows to Run Python Unittests

The pom.xml is configured with the exec-maven-plugin, which specifies commands that Maven should run during the build process. In the configuration provided earlier, the exec-maven-plugin is set up to activate a Python virtual environment and run Python tests in the unittests/ directory.

Here’s how Maven knows to run the Python tests:

1. exec-maven-plugin Configuration in pom.xml:

The exec-maven-plugin in the pom.xml was configured with a script that:

<plugin>
    <groupId>org.codehaus.mojo</groupId>
    <artifactId>exec-maven-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>3.0.0</version>
    <executions>
        <execution>
            <id>run-python-tests</id>
            <phase>test</phase> <!-- This links it to the Maven test phase -->
            <goals>
                <goal>exec</goal>
            </goals>
            <configuration>
                <executable>sh</executable>
                <arguments>
                    <argument>-c</argument>
                    <argument>
                        source venv/bin/activate &amp;&amp; pytest unittests/ --junitxml=report.xml
                    </argument>
                </arguments>
            </configuration>
        </execution>
    </executions>
</plugin>

Explanation:

During the test phase of the Maven build, the plugin executes the script:

source venv/bin/activate && pytest unittests/ --junitxml=report.xml

This command activates the Python virtual environment and runs pytest in the unittests/ directory.

It expects the Python tests to be located in the unittests/ directory in your repository.




2. No Need to Include the unittests Folder in the <include> Tag:

The <include> tag in the pom.xml under the maven-lps-plugin or any similar packaging plugin is used for including specific folders or files in the final package/archive.

This is usually used for non-standard files or folders you want to include in your deployable artifact, such as scripts or resources.

In your case, the unittests/ folder is not something you would want to package for deployment, so you don't need to add it there.



3. How Jenkins Executes the Unittests:

The Jenkinsfile triggers the Maven build using the runMaven function.

When Maven reaches the test phase, the exec-maven-plugin runs the Python tests defined in the pom.xml.

Jenkins, via the Jenkinsfile, is only responsible for invoking the Maven build process and setting up the environment (like the Python virtual environment).




Summary of Required Steps:

1. Ensure unittests/ is in Your Repository:

The unittests/ folder should be in your repository at the root level (or in the expected path relative to where Maven is run).



2. Ensure exec-maven-plugin Configuration is Correct:

Verify that the exec-maven-plugin configuration in the pom.xml points to the correct directory and file structure for your Python tests.

Example:

<configuration>
    <executable>sh</executable>
    <arguments>
        <argument>-c</argument>
        <argument>
            source venv/bin/activate && pytest unittests/ --junitxml=report.xml
        </argument>
    </arguments>
</configuration>



3. No Need to Add unittests to <include>:

The unittests/ directory is for testing purposes and is not required in the final build artifact.

Leave the <include> section in the maven-lps-plugin or any other packaging plugin as it is unless there is a specific reason to package the unittests folder.




By following these guidelines, Maven and Jenkins will correctly execute your Python unittests during the build process without the need to include the unittests/ folder in the package. If you need further clarification or assistance, feel free to ask!


